<speak version="1.0" xml:lang="en-US" xmlns:mstts="http://www.w3.org/2001/mstts"><voice name="en-US-JennyNeural"><prosody rate="0%" pitch="+0st"><p><mark name="L1.S1"/>Welcome to our lesson on cells. <break time="400ms"/> A cell is the smallest unit of life, serving as the building block for all living organisms. <break time="400ms"/> Cells perform essential functions that sustain life.</p><p><mark name="L1.S2"/>There are two main types of cells: prokaryotic and eukaryotic. <break time="400ms"/> Prokaryotic cells are simple and lack a nucleus, while eukaryotic cells are more complex and contain a nucleus.</p><p><mark name="L1.S3"/>In summary, cells are fundamental to life, and understanding the differences between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells is crucial for studying biology.</p></prosody></voice></speak>